---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import CTABlock from '../../components/CTABlock.astro';
import { business, BASE } from '../../data/business';
import { postBySlug } from '../../data/posts';

const post = postBySlug('hiring-handyman-troon-7-questions')!;
const siteUrl = business.siteUrl.replace(/\/$/, '');
const url = `${siteUrl}/blog/${post.slug}/`;
const ogImage = `${siteUrl}${post.ogImage}`;

const articleSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  '@id': `${url}#article`,
  headline: post.title,
  description: post.description,
  inLanguage: 'en-GB',
  datePublished: post.date,
  dateModified: post.date,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Person',
    name: post.author,
    worksFor: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  },
  publisher: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  image: [ogImage],
  mainEntityOfPage: url,
  articleSection: 'Hiring a handyman',
  keywords: [post.keyword, 'hiring handyman troon', 'insured handyman ayrshire', 'holiday home handyman troon', 'handyman quote troon'],
  wordCount: post.wordCount,
  about: { '@type': 'Place', name: 'Troon, Scotland' },
};
---
<BaseLayout
  title={`${post.title} | Sorn Handyman Services`}
  description={post.description}
  canonicalPath={`/blog/${post.slug}/`}
  ogImage={ogImage}
  extraSchema={articleSchema}
>
  <Breadcrumbs trail={[
    { name: 'Home', href: `${BASE}/` },
    { name: 'Blog', href: `${BASE}/blog/` },
    { name: post.title },
  ]} />

  <article class="container-x py-10 lg:py-14 max-w-3xl">
    <header>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-amber-600">
        <span>{post.area}</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <span class="text-navy-900/60">{post.readMinutes} min read</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <time datetime={post.date} class="text-navy-900/60">{post.dateDisplay}</time>
      </div>
      <h1 class="mt-4 font-serif text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-navy-900 leading-tight">
        {post.title}
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-5 text-lg text-navy-900/75">
        Troon is full of second homes, holiday lets and people who just want
        something done right the first time. If you're trusting a stranger
        with a set of keys, these seven questions will save you a lot of grief.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="prose-sorn mt-8 text-lg">
      <p>
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/troon/`}>Troon</a> has a specific problem when
        it comes to trades: a lot of the houses belong to people who don't
        live there every day. Second homes. Family inheritances. Holiday lets.
        Retirement properties bought by folk who still work in Glasgow. That
        makes it a great patch for an honest handyman — and a nightmare if
        you pick the wrong one, because you might not set foot in the place
        for three weeks after the job's "finished".
      </p>
      <p>
        I cover Troon from our base in Sorn and I've been in a lot of houses
        where the last handyman cut corners because nobody was going to check.
        So here are the seven questions I'd ask any tradesman in Troon before
        I booked — including me. If a handyman can't give you a straight
        answer to all of them, keep looking.
      </p>

      <h2>1. "Are you insured, and can you send me the certificate?"</h2>
      <p>
        Not "are you insured". Ask for the certificate. Any handyman worth
        ringing carries public liability insurance — ours is £2 million — and
        will have the PDF saved on their phone. If they promise to send it
        and then don't, that's your answer. Book someone else.
      </p>
      <p>
        Insurance matters most when nothing has gone wrong for years, because
        that's exactly when you stop checking. The day a tile comes off a
        roof onto a neighbour's car in Troon is the day insurance saves
        everybody a £2,000 headache.
      </p>

      <h2>2. "What's your trade background?"</h2>
      <p>
        "Handyman" is not a regulated word in the UK. Anyone can print the
        card. Ask what they actually trained in.
      </p>
      <p>
        A real answer sounds like <em>"I'm a time-served joiner, 20 years
        on site"</em> or <em>"I'm a qualified plumber and mechanical engineer,
        my dad's a joiner, we work together"</em>. A vague answer —
        <em>"I've been doing this a few years"</em> — means you're paying
        for on-the-job learning. Fine for a flat-pack wardrobe. Not fine for
        a bathroom refit in a holiday let.
      </p>

      <h2>3. "Can I have a written quote, broken down line by line?"</h2>
      <p>
        Verbal quotes vanish. Written quotes don't. Any job over about £200
        should come with an emailed or WhatsApp'd quote that lists materials,
        labour, VAT status and timeframe separately.
      </p>
      <p>
        Line-by-line matters because it lets you compare like-for-like and
        it makes it almost impossible to slip extras on at the end. If the
        quote is one line — <em>"Bathroom repair: £1,200"</em> — you have
        no leverage when it somehow becomes £1,600 at invoice time. We write
        every quote over £200 as a clear itemised document with a fixed-price
        lock on it. No surprises.
      </p>

      <h2>4. "Do you charge a call-out fee for the quote?"</h2>
      <p>
        Some trades do, some don't. It's not a red flag either way — but
        know before they arrive. The worst version is when the call-out fee
        gets "waived if you book the work" on the day — which puts you under
        pressure to book there and then. We don't charge call-out fees
        anywhere in <a href={`${BASE}/areas/troon/`}>Troon</a>,
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/ayr/`}>Ayr</a> or
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/`}>our East Ayrshire patch</a>. The quote is
        free, you have as long as you want to decide, we won't chase you.
      </p>

      <h2>5. "Who actually does the work — you or someone you send?"</h2>
      <p>
        This is the question that catches out a lot of bigger handyman firms.
        The person answering the phone and giving you the quote might not be
        the person showing up with the drill. That's fine if the handyman you
        speak to is upfront about it — and a red flag if they dodge the
        question.
      </p>
      <p>
        For us the answer is simple: it's me (Aidan) or my dad Fraser, every
        time. Two of us, same van, no subcontractors. If you want a specific
        one of us because one trade suits the job better, say so — Fraser's
        the joiner, I'm the plumber. We don't mind.
      </p>

      <h2>6. "What's the warranty on the work?"</h2>
      <p>
        Materials usually carry a manufacturer warranty — that's not the
        question. Ask about the <em>labour</em>. A proper tradesman will
        stand behind their own workmanship for at least 12 months. If a
        joint we soldered leaks in six months, we come back and fix it for
        free. If a bit of joinery we fitted has warped, same.
      </p>
      <p>
        Ask for this in writing too. "Yeah aye, we'll sort it" isn't a
        warranty. "12 months on all workmanship, no quibble" in the quote
        document, is.
      </p>

      <h2>7. "Can I see a local job and speak to the customer?"</h2>
      <p>
        This is the strongest filter of the lot, and most folk don't ask
        because they're embarrassed to. Don't be. Any handyman who's been
        working in Troon more than six months has done jobs for people who'd
        happily vouch. We'll give you two or three names and numbers on
        request — obviously only customers who've said they're happy to
        chat.
      </p>
      <p>
        Even better, ask to see a job in the area that's still standing 18
        months on. A deck. A bathroom. A fence. The photo from the day of
        completion is easy. The one from 18 months later is the real test.
      </p>

      <h2>The short version, if you're in a rush</h2>
      <p>
        You want a tradesman in Troon who: carries insurance and will prove
        it, has a genuine trade background, writes quotes line-by-line, doesn't
        surprise you with call-out fees, tells you straight who's turning up,
        stands behind their own labour for a year, and can point you at a
        real local customer.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you find three who tick all seven, pick the one you <em>like</em>.
        Trades work is a relationship — especially for a second home. The one
        who answers the phone straight, gives you a straight quote and doesn't
        waffle is the one to book.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you want to try us,
        <a href={`tel:${business.phoneE164}`}>call {business.phone}</a>,
        <a href={`https://wa.me/${business.whatsapp.replace('+','')}`}>WhatsApp a photo</a>, or
        <a href={`${BASE}/quote/`}>send us a quote request here</a>. We answer
        every message — day, night, weekend. No call-centre, no gatekeepers.
        Just me or Fraser.
      </p>

      <div class="not-prose mt-10 rounded-2xl border border-navy-900/10 bg-navy-50/50 p-6">
        <p class="text-sm text-navy-900/60">Written by</p>
        <p class="mt-1 font-serif text-xl font-bold text-navy-900">{post.author}</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-navy-900/75 text-sm">{post.authorBio}</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <CTABlock
    heading="Looking for a straight-talking handyman in Troon?"
    sub="Tell us what needs doing — photo on WhatsApp if it's easier. We'll answer every question above before you book."
    location="Troon"
  />
</BaseLayout>
